    <article class="prose dark:prose-invert max-w-none">
      <h2>How to Use the Cost Per Km Calculator</h2>
      <p>
        This calculator helps you determine the exact fuel cost for every kilometer you drive. Enter the total distance you traveled in kilometers, the amount of fuel your vehicle consumed in liters, and the price you paid per liter of fuel. The calculator instantly shows your cost per kilometer, the equivalent cost per mile, and the total fuel expenditure for the trip.
      </p>
      <p>
        Knowing your cost per kilometer is essential for budgeting daily commutes, planning road trips, and comparing the fuel efficiency of different vehicles. Fleet managers, delivery drivers, and rideshare operators use this metric to track operational costs and set competitive pricing. You can also use it to compare the running costs of a petrol car against a diesel or electric vehicle.
      </p>

      <div class="my-6"><%= render "shared/ad_slot", slot: "in_content" %></div>

      <h2>Cost Per Km Formula</h2>
      <p>
        The formula is straightforward: <strong>Cost per km = (Fuel Used x Price per Liter) / Distance in km</strong>. To convert to cost per mile, multiply the cost per km by 1.60934. For example, if you drove 500 km using 45 liters of fuel at $1.40 per liter, your cost per km is (45 x $1.40) / 500 = $0.126. That equates to roughly $0.20 per mile.
      </p>

      <h3>Tracking Fuel Costs Over Time</h3>
      <p>
        Calculating your cost per km after every fill-up lets you spot trends in vehicle efficiency. Seasonal changes, tire condition, driving habits, and fuel quality all affect consumption. By keeping a simple log of distance, fuel, and price, you can identify when your vehicle is running less efficiently and take corrective action before costs spiral. Many drivers find that consistent tracking saves them hundreds of dollars per year.
      </p>

      <h3>Comparing Vehicles by Cost Per Km</h3>
      <p>
        When shopping for a new car, cost per km gives a clearer picture than manufacturer fuel economy ratings alone, because it accounts for real-world driving conditions and local fuel prices. Calculate the cost per km for your current vehicle first, then estimate it for alternatives based on their rated consumption and the fuel price you typically pay. This comparison reveals true savings potential beyond the sticker price.
      </p>

      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <h3>How do I calculate cost per kilometer?</h3>
      <p>
        Divide the total fuel cost by the distance driven in kilometers. Total fuel cost equals fuel used (in liters) multiplied by the price per liter. For example, if you used 40 liters at $1.50 per liter to drive 500 km, the cost per km is (40 x $1.50) / 500 = $0.12 per km.
      </p>

      <h3>How do I convert cost per km to cost per mile?</h3>
      <p>
        Multiply the cost per kilometer by 1.60934 to get the cost per mile. Since one mile equals 1.60934 kilometers, a cost of $0.10 per km equals approximately $0.16 per mile.
      </p>

      <h3>What is a good cost per kilometer for a car?</h3>
      <p>
        A good cost per km depends on fuel prices and vehicle efficiency. In most regions, $0.05 to $0.15 per km for fuel alone is typical for passenger cars. Electric vehicles can achieve $0.02 to $0.05 per km. Diesel vehicles often fall between $0.06 and $0.12 per km.
      </p>

      <h3>Does cost per km include maintenance and insurance?</h3>
      <p>
        This calculator focuses on fuel cost per km only. The total cost of ownership per km also includes maintenance, insurance, depreciation, registration, and financing costs. The fuel cost typically represents 20-30% of total per-km vehicle running costs.
      </p>

      <h3>How can I reduce my cost per kilometer?</h3>
      <p>
        Drive at steady speeds, avoid aggressive acceleration and braking, maintain correct tire pressure, reduce excess weight in the vehicle, use cruise control on highways, and keep up with regular maintenance. Choosing routes with less traffic and fewer stops also improves fuel efficiency and reduces cost per km.
      </p>

